Stimuli - those powerful forces!<br>
Hey, P.P. Paul Pagemaker, I told you and Ed not to pick your nose when you post. Stimulus equals response, it'll happen every time. <br><br>
Actually I think its a commie virus, happened to me above. Before I had a chance to fill in the blanks it posted on me. Make it stop, make it stop. <br>
Even since Ed shot that old, blind and crippled Deer, things haven't been the same. <br><br>
Ed, I like the peaks and I like the valleys, can’t appreciate the good times unless we’ve experienced the bad. Jukeboxes are fine, especially those that play the tunes of the 60’s. Agree about Denny's why can't they serve peaches and pound cakes.<br>
Why didn’t the Vietnam war have its own song? <br>
I mean WWII vets had that “Wasting Matilda” song. <br>
“Eve of Destruction,” was the closest I can think of, with its lyrics of, “You’re old enough to kill, but not for voting, you don’t believe in war, but what’s that gun you’re toting.” Or something like that. There are some songs that do trigger some memories, Sentimental Journey and others. Sometimes when I hear them I recall some very fond memories. <br><br>
Late summer 1967, Hill 65, Guns bunker.<br>
”All of us sitting around,  Boone and Boyd inside the hooch along with Jones and Porter all of them jamming to the sounds that's coming from the portable juice box. They all made quite a sight-- little Jones, gold cap tooth glistening in the candle light, tall Boone wearing his black beret cap, heavily built Boyd who just didn't seem to fit in with the group, and Porter who was just happy to be included with any group. <br>
Jones had taken the arm off of the top record on the record player so that Stevie Wonders', &quot;I Was Made to Love Her,&quot; played over and over again. <br><br>
Outside the hooch and under the porch was Bro, John, Keeton, Ken Stoker, who wore a silk stocking around his helmet and was a true grunt, a Marines Marine. <br>
Then there was Turner, Chief, Joe Cervantez and myself. Joe was a new man recently assigned to 1st squad. He had already been tagged with the name &quot;Lucky&quot; for some reason, but if I remember correctly he wasn’t really very lucky. He was the one that fell into a flooded bomb crater and we all had to fish him out, what a night that was. Gee, those were great guys. <br>
Bro and Ken were killed. Turner got shot nine times, wish I could see him again. Boone became a Muslim and disappeared. Porter was never really there, don’t know if I want to find him. Jones I would love to see again, Boyd, John, Keeton I’ve spoken too, all of them are doing great. Never knew what happened to Joe, I think he made it home, but I figured he’s either in jail or dead, like Tired Aggie and Nasty Nick. Think I’ll call Marty tonight. <br>
Good night guys.<br>

